   =20
      XRP ETF
   =20
 =20

Similarly, if you want to set up an exchange-traded fund that will offer re=
tail investors an easy way to invest in some cryptocurrency, there are many=
 steps, but one of them =E2=80=94=C2=A0one of the first=C2=A0public=C2=A0st=
eps =E2=80=94=C2=A0is to file paperwork with the Delaware Department of Sta=
te to set up the trust for the ETF. If you want to pretend to set up a cryp=
to ETF, you can just do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0again, you probably pay about a=
 three-digit filing fee =E2=80=94=C2=A0and not do the rest.
If you file for =E2=80=9CMatt=E2=80=99s Ripple ETF Trust,=E2=80=9D no one w=
ill care, though. Pretending that you will set up a crypto ETF is worthless=
. The move is to pretend that=C2=A0BlackRock=C2=A0will set up a crypto ETF.=
 Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Vildana Hajric reports:

A filing for a BlackRock Inc. fund based on the cryptocurrency XRP showed u=
p on the official Delaware website that registers investment trusts incorpo=
rated in the state, triggering a brief rally in the token. The only problem=
 is that BlackRock wasn=E2=80=99t the one who submitted it.
The Delaware Department of State=E2=80=99s Division of Corporations website=
 =E2=80=94 which lists some other trusts the asset manager has applied for =
previously =E2=80=94 showed details for something called the =E2=80=9CiShar=
es XRP Trust=E2=80=9D registered to BlackRock on Monday. A spokesperson for=
 the asset manager, however, confirmed that it=E2=80=99s false.
XRP briefly spiked almost 13% as news about the fake filing made its rounds=
 on X, the social-media platform formerly known as Twitter. It gave back th=
ose gains to trade lower on the day. The token is one of the largest crypto=
currencies =E2=80=94 ranking fifth on the CoinGecko website =E2=80=94 thoug=
h it=E2=80=99s lesser known than Bitcoin and Ether.

Why would you want to pretend that BlackRock is setting up an XRP ETF? I su=
ppose there is some outside possibility of =E2=80=9Cyou enjoy trolling peop=
le on Twitter and are willing to pay a bit of money to do that.=E2=80=9D Bu=
t realistically it=E2=80=99s market manipulation.

 =20
   =20
      BTIG vs. StoneX
   =20
 =20

The problem is that, if you are stealing trade secrets from your security-c=
onscious financial services employer, you will either do it carelessly, or =
you will do it cleverly and secretly. If you do it carelessly, your securit=
y-conscious financial services employer will probably catch you. If you do =
it cleverly and secretly, with subtle tradecraft that evades your employer=
=E2=80=99s detection systems, you will be proud of yourself. =E2=80=9CLook =
at me,=E2=80=9D you will think, =E2=80=9CI am basically James Bond.=E2=80=
=9D You will smile, satisfied in the knowledge that you=E2=80=99d be an exc=
ellent spy. For like two minutes. Then that knowledge will not be satisfyin=
g enough without telling someone. You will text your friends, accomplices, =
whoever, to be like =E2=80=9Clook at me, I am basically James Bond, please =
admire my tradecraft.=E2=80=9D Eventually you will tell enough people about=
 your brilliant tradecraft that it will get back to your security-conscious=
 financial services employer and you will get in trouble.
I suppose that is not=C2=A0always=C2=A0true. Maybe some financial services =
employees are basically James Bond. But quite a few of them seem to like be=
ing spies, but only if they can tell everyone. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Zek=
e Faux and Robert Burnson report:

Brokerage firm BTIG LLC accused StoneX Group Inc., a rival brokerage and in=
vestment bank, of stealing its proprietary software code in what its lawyer=
s describe as =E2=80=9Cone of the greatest financial-industry trade secret =
frauds in recent history.=E2=80=9D
BTIG made the claim in a lawsuit filed late Monday in California state cour=
t and seeks at least $200 million in damages.
BTIG is an investment bank and trading firm, with expertise in trading stoc=
ks for institutional clients, including foreign stocks and exchange-traded =
funds. In 2020, according to the lawsuit, StoneX set out to build its own e=
quities market-making business. But to do so, the firm recruited several ke=
y BTIG traders and software developers.
Some of them stole BTIG=E2=80=99s proprietary computer code and took it wit=
h them to StoneX, according to the suit. BTIG accused its rival of lying ab=
out the misconduct even when confronted with evidence.

Here is  the complaint, which is really everything you could hope for in a =
case like this. (Several pages are entirely blacked out by redactions, for =
instance.) One BTIG engineer,=C2=A0Evan Pfeuffer, allegedly did some pretty=
 good tradecraft to extract code secretly:
Based on a subsequent forensic review, Pfeuffer logged onto BTIG servers to=
 collect and remove key code. Because BTIG=E2=80=99s servers had sophistica=
ted defenses against exfiltration of code, Pfeuffer resorted to extraordina=
ry measures. Pfeuffer took large swathes of code and other proprietary info=
rmation and encrypted them using NSA-level encryption techniques, rendering=
 the payload a meaningless string of gobbledygook to anyone without the enc=
ryption key. Pfeuffer then appended the encrypted code to pdf versions of g=
eneric documents that were downloaded from the internet; anyone looking at =
the files would see a generic PDF document that when opened presented itsel=
f as normal, but in fact had code and other information secretly appended i=
nside. Pfeuffer then used BTIG=E2=80=99s automated email server for sending=
 client reports to email the PDFs =E2=80=93 with the encrypted code appende=
d =E2=80=93 to himself, and then he took the code through various means out=
side BTIG. Once outside BTIG, Pfeuffer could take out the encrypted code, d=
ecrypt it, transfer it to StoneX and then use it at StoneX.
Sure, terrific.
  [5]
=C2=A0But he was also texting with a StoneX engineer and couldn=E2=80=99t r=
esist describing this scheme with a combination of accurate technical detai=
ls and pop-culture quotes:

Text messages between Pfeuffer and the StoneX software engineer confirm the=
 scheme. On February 8, 2021 =E2=80=93 days after Pfeuffer resigned from BT=
IG =E2=80=93 the StoneX engineer asked Pfeuffer, =E2=80=9Cdidn=E2=80=99t yo=
u append pdf for your stuff,=E2=80=9D to which Pfeuffer responded =E2=80=9C=
Ah didn=E2=80=99t realize what u were taking (sic) about, yeah, hidden encr=
ypted payload appended to pdf. I=E2=80=99ve got mine prepared going to test=
 tomorrow, keep it secret, keep it safe. Like the ring.=E2=80=9D
  [6]

Two days later, Pfeuffer texted the StoneX engineer, =E2=80=9CThe eagle has=
 landed, code extracted.=E2=80=9D

If you find yourself saying =E2=80=9Ckeep it secret, keep it safe,=E2=80=9D=
 about the encrypted trade secrets that you laboriously smuggled out of you=
r security-conscious employer, in a text message, something has gone wrong.
A lot of what is going on here is=C2=A0sort of a standard poaching dispute:=
 A BTIG employee left for StoneX to build a competing business, he naturall=
y brought over some of his BTIG friends, and so there are arguable violatio=
ns of their various non-compete and non-solicitation clauses. Also whenever=
 this happens the jilted employer can say =E2=80=9Cand you brought your kno=
wledge of our trade secrets and computer code with you,=E2=80=9D and often =
that is true but hard to prove. And sometimes the jilted employer can say =
=E2=80=9Calso you brought over this specific repository of code with you,=
=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0can=C2=A0prove it =E2=80=94=C2=A0by pointing to the docu=
ments they emailed to themselves, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then it has a mor=
e compelling case, though even there the other side can argue things like =
=E2=80=9Cit is not actually rocket science to build a computer program to q=
uote equities, and what these guys took was not really a valuable trade sec=
ret,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cmaybe they emailed this stuff to themselves but t=
hey did not actually use it in our systems, which are totally different and=
 much better.=E2=80=9D
One other thing that is happening here is that, if you are a firm that argu=
ably poaches employees=C2=A0and intellectual property from other firms, tha=
t gives=C2=A0your employees some leverage against you. How did BTIG find ou=
t all this stuff about what StoneX was doing? Some of it is from its own mo=
nitoring of its email systems, PDF exfiltration, etc. But some of it is fro=
m a disgruntled StoneX employee:

In January 2023, in connection with a lawsuit between StoneX and one of its=
 former employees, a StoneX engineer who worked with both Bhaduri and Pfeuf=
fer to develop software code for StoneX revealed a scheme by the Disloyal E=
mployees and StoneX to incorporate BTIG=E2=80=99s=C2=A0proprietary code int=
o StoneX=E2=80=99s quantitative trading platform that, in the year and a ha=
lf since it had been implemented, had generated =E2=80=9Cmillions of dollar=
s using BTIG=E2=80=99s trade secrets.=E2=80=9D
Specifically, the whistleblower explained that Pfeuffer incorporated BTIG=
=E2=80=99s proprietary code into StoneX=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CTampa=E2=80=9D s=
oftware code, a critical component of StoneX=E2=80=99s marketmaking applica=
tions system. The software engineer further explained that he =E2=80=9Cdisc=
overed numerous references to BTIG in the Tampa code itself . . . and had d=
iscovered a reference to [BTIG=E2=80=99s Managing Director of Technology] i=
n StoneX=E2=80=99s Tampa code.=E2=80=9D It alleges that, according to elect=
ronic log records, Pfeuffer checked BTIG=E2=80=99s source code into StoneX=
=E2=80=99s system and incorporated it into StoneX=E2=80=99s code.

One possibility is=C2=A0that if you are a BTIG engineer and you have techno=
logy that StoneX wants, the way to monetize that is to take a job at StoneX=
 and smuggle code out appended to PDFs. And if you are a StoneX engineer an=
d you have technology that BTIG provided, the way to monetize that is to go=
 to BTIG and say =E2=80=9Chey I know something interesting, what might=C2=
=A0it be=C2=A0worth to you.=E2=80=9D

