<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that, if you are stealing trade=
 secrets from your security-conscious financial services employer, you will=
 either do it carelessly, or you will do it cleverly and secretly. If you d=
o it carelessly, your security-conscious financial services employer will p=
robably catch you. If you do it cleverly and secretly, with subtle tradecra=
ft that evades your employer=E2=80=99s detection systems, you will be proud=
 of yourself. =E2=80=9CLook at me,=E2=80=9D you will think, =E2=80=9CI am b=
asically James Bond.=E2=80=9D You will smile, satisfied in the knowledge th=
at you=E2=80=99d be an excellent spy. For like two minutes. Then that knowl=
edge will not be satisfying enough without telling someone. You will text y=
our friends, accomplices, whoever, to be like =E2=80=9Clook at me, I am bas=
ically James Bond, please admire my tradecraft.=E2=80=9D Eventually you wil=
l tell enough people about your brilliant tradecraft that it will get back =
to your security-conscious financial services employer and you will get in =
trouble.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose that is not=C2=A0<em>always=C2=A0</e=
m>true. Maybe some financial services employees are basically James Bond. B=
ut quite a few of them seem to like being spies, but only if they can tell =
everyone. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/33377885.258417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMTQvYnRpZy1hY2N1c2VzLXJpdmFsLWJyb2tlci1zdG9uZXgtb2Ytc=
3RlYWxpbmctdHJhZGluZy10ZWNobm9sb2d5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMTUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0=
bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTExNSZ1dG1=
fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB38b60afd" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Zeke=
 Faux and Robert Burnson report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Brokerage firm BTIG LLC accused StoneX Group I=
nc., a rival brokerage and investment bank, of stealing its proprietary sof=
tware code in what its lawyers describe as =E2=80=9Cone of the greatest fin=
ancial-industry trade secret frauds in recent history.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BTIG made the claim in a lawsuit filed late Mo=
nday in California state court and seeks at least $200 million in damages.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BTIG is an investment bank and trading firm, w=
ith expertise in trading stocks for institutional clients, including foreig=
n stocks and exchange-traded funds. In 2020, according to the lawsuit, Ston=
eX set out to build its own equities market-making business. But to do so, =
the firm recruited several key BTIG traders and software developers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of them stole BTIG=E2=80=99s proprietary =
computer code and took it with them to StoneX, according to the suit. BTIG =
accused its rival of lying about the misconduct even when confronted with e=
vidence.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/33377885.258417/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVu=
dHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3IucDRiVHBoTnA3ay92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B2d09d587" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> the complaint</a>, which is really everything you could=
 hope for in a case like this. (Several pages are entirely blacked out by r=
edactions, for instance.) One BTIG engineer,=C2=A0Evan Pfeuffer, allegedly =
did some pretty good tradecraft to extract code secretly:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Based on a subsequent forensic rev=
iew, Pfeuffer logged onto BTIG servers to collect and remove key code. Beca=
use BTIG=E2=80=99s servers had sophisticated defenses against exfiltration =
of code, Pfeuffer resorted to extraordinary measures. Pfeuffer took large s=
wathes of code and other proprietary information and encrypted them using N=
SA-level encryption techniques, rendering the payload a meaningless string =
of gobbledygook to anyone without the encryption key. Pfeuffer then appende=
d the encrypted code to pdf versions of generic documents that were downloa=
ded from the internet; anyone looking at the files would see a generic PDF =
document that when opened presented itself as normal, but in fact had code =
and other information secretly appended inside. Pfeuffer then used BTIG=E2=
=80=99s automated email server for sending client reports to email the PDFs=
 =E2=80=93 with the encrypted code appended =E2=80=93 to himself, and then =
he took the code through various means outside BTIG. Once outside BTIG, Pfe=
uffer could take out the encrypted code, decrypt it, transfer it to StoneX =
and then use it at StoneX.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure, terrific.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But he was also texting with a StoneX engineer and couldn=E2=80=
=99t resist describing this scheme with a combination of accurate technical=
 details and pop-culture quotes:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Text messages between Pfeuffer and the StoneX =
software engineer confirm the scheme. On February 8, 2021 =E2=80=93 days af=
ter Pfeuffer resigned from BTIG =E2=80=93 the StoneX engineer asked Pfeuffe=
r, =E2=80=9Cdidn=E2=80=99t you append pdf for your stuff,=E2=80=9D to which=
 Pfeuffer responded =E2=80=9CAh didn=E2=80=99t realize what u were taking (=
sic) about, yeah, hidden encrypted payload appended to pdf. I=E2=80=99ve go=
t mine prepared going to test tomorrow, keep it secret, keep it safe. Like =
the ring.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two days later, Pfeuffer texted the StoneX eng=
ineer, =E2=80=9CThe eagle has landed, code extracted.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you find yourself saying =E2=80=9Ckeep it s=
ecret, keep it safe,=E2=80=9D about the encrypted trade secrets that you la=
boriously smuggled out of your security-conscious employer, <em>in a text m=
essage</em>, something has gone wrong.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of what is going on here is=C2=A0sort of=
 a standard poaching dispute: A BTIG employee left for StoneX to build a co=
mpeting business, he naturally brought over some of his BTIG friends, and s=
o there are arguable violations of their various non-compete and non-solici=
tation clauses. Also whenever this happens the jilted employer can say =E2=
=80=9Cand you brought your knowledge of our trade secrets and computer code=
 with you,=E2=80=9D and often that is true but hard to prove. And sometimes=
 the jilted employer can say =E2=80=9Calso you brought over this specific r=
epository of code with you,=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>prove it =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0by pointing to the documents they emailed to themselves, etc=
. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then it has a more compelling case, though even there =
the other side can argue things like =E2=80=9Cit is not actually rocket sci=
ence to build a computer program to quote equities, and what these guys too=
k was not really a valuable trade secret,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cmaybe they e=
mailed this stuff to themselves but they did not actually use it in our sys=
tems, which are totally different and much better.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One other thing that is happening here is that=
, if you are a firm that arguably poaches employees=C2=A0and intellectual p=
roperty from other firms, that gives=C2=A0<em>your </em>employees some leve=
rage against <em>you</em>. How did BTIG find out all this stuff about what =
StoneX was doing? Some of it is from its own monitoring of its email system=
s, PDF exfiltration, etc. But some of it is from a disgruntled StoneX emplo=
yee:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In January 2023, in connection with a lawsuit =
between StoneX and one of its former employees, a StoneX engineer who worke=
d with both Bhaduri and Pfeuffer to develop software code for StoneX reveal=
ed a scheme by the Disloyal Employees and StoneX to incorporate BTIG=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0proprietary code into StoneX=E2=80=99s quantitative trading platf=
orm that, in the year and a half since it had been implemented, had generat=
ed =E2=80=9Cmillions of dollars using BTIG=E2=80=99s trade secrets.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically, the whistleblower explained that=
 Pfeuffer incorporated BTIG=E2=80=99s proprietary code into StoneX=E2=80=99=
s =E2=80=9CTampa=E2=80=9D software code, a critical component of StoneX=E2=
=80=99s marketmaking applications system. The software engineer further exp=
lained that he =E2=80=9Cdiscovered numerous references to BTIG in the Tampa=
 code itself . . . and had discovered a reference to [BTIG=E2=80=99s Managi=
ng Director of Technology] in StoneX=E2=80=99s Tampa code.=E2=80=9D It alle=
ges that, according to electronic log records, Pfeuffer checked BTIG=E2=80=
=99s source code into StoneX=E2=80=99s system and incorporated it into Ston=
eX=E2=80=99s code.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One possibility is=C2=A0that if you are a BTIG=
 engineer and you have technology that StoneX wants, the way to monetize th=
at is to take a job at StoneX and smuggle code out appended to PDFs. And if=
 you are a StoneX engineer and you have technology that BTIG provided, the =
way to monetize that is to go to BTIG and say =E2=80=9Chey I know something=
 interesting, what might=C2=A0it be=C2=A0worth to you.=E2=80=9D</p>
