adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Tether vs. USDC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A stablecoin is a way to hold US dollars (or e=
uros, etc.) in a way that is convenient for crypto. You buy cryptocurrencie=
s on some crypto blockchain and hold them in some crypto wallet; a stableco=
in is a cryptocurrency on a crypto blockchain in a crypto wallet, but it is=
 worth a dollar.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People want this=C2=A0for two main reasons. On=
e is that if you trade a lot of crypto, you will sometimes close positions =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0you will buy some crypto and then, later, sell it =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and the natural way to close a position is into dollars. You measure =
your profits and losses in dollars, you pay your rent in dollars, so you ef=
fectively trade between crypto and dollars. And if you are doing a lot of t=
hat, you will find that holding dollars in the form of stablecoins is more =
convenient and efficient than holding dollars in the form of a bank account=
 (or money-market fund, or pile of $20 bills). Your stablecoin-dollars live=
 on the blockchain and are instantly transferable for crypto within the cry=
pto system; your regular dollars live in a bank that might be slow or fussy=
 about transferring them to a crypto exchange. The stablecoin is a way to k=
eep all of your trading <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/33377885.258417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMTktMDEtMDkvYmxvY2tjaGFpbi1zdG9jay1vZmZlcmluZ3MtYW5kLXN0YWJsZWNvaW5zLXdp=
bGwtZW5oYW5jZS1jcnlwdG8_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1=
lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj=
1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB728e7b24" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> within the crypt=
o system</a>, but without always being exposed to crypto prices.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other, almost unrelated reason is that the=
re are people who find the crypto financial system more accessible than the=
 regular US dollar financial system. People in countries with fragile banki=
ng systems, people in countries with high inflation, but also various kinds=
 of criminals,=C2=A0all might say =E2=80=9CI would rather keep my money in =
crypto than in a bank.=E2=80=9D These people are not trying to trade freque=
ntly or speculate on crypto; they just want to hold their money somewhere s=
afe, and for whatever reason that is not, for them, a bank.=C2=A0But crypto=
currencies are volatile, while US dollar-linked stablecoins mostly aren=E2=
=80=99t. So =E2=80=9CI would rather keep my money in crypto than in a bank,=
 but in dollars=E2=80=9D is a reasonable thing for these people to think.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another important thing about stablecoins is t=
hat they mostly don=E2=80=99t pay interest. The main mechanism of a stablec=
oin is that you deposit dollars with a stablecoin issuer, they give you bac=
k a stablecoin (a token on the blockchain), and=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>put=
 the dollar into a bank account (or Treasury bills, or Chinese real estate =
commercial paper, or whatever). And they keep the interest and you don=E2=
=80=99t. In a world of zero interest rates that was fine. In a world of 5% =
short-term interest rates it makes being a stablecoin issuer insanely lucra=
tive. But also the customers notice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you could wave a magic wand and make crypto=
=C2=A0<em>totally mainstream</em>, what would that do to the demand for sta=
blecoins? I don=E2=80=99t know, but my intuition is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The people who use stablecoins for tr=
ading crypto would stop doing that. Their banks and brokerages would be hap=
py to send money to crypto exchanges, the rails for converting dollars into=
 crypto would be fast and highly functional, and it would be equally conven=
ient, for a crypto trader, to hold dollars in a bank or in a stablecoin. Bu=
t the bank pays interest and the stablecoin does not.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The people who use stablecoins be=
cause they are unbanked would still very much want to do that. Embracing cr=
ypto within the regular US financial system would not help them. Perhaps it=
 would hurt them; I don=E2=80=99t know exactly what it means for crypto to =
be =E2=80=9Ctotally mainstream,=E2=80=9D but if it meant that all of crypto=
 was run out of big regulated financial institutions then people who are un=
banked now would be un-crypto-banked in that world. But if they could still=
 get 0%-yielding stablecoins, but not bank accounts, they=E2=80=99d still w=
ant that.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two big stablecoin issuers are Circle (whose t=
oken is USDC) and Tether (whose token is often called Tether, or else USDT)=
. Circle is a US company that is sort of a bet on crypto being mainstream a=
nd regulated and respectable. Tether is exactly the opposite of that. Circl=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33377885.258417/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2lyY2xlLmNvbS9lbi90cmFuc3BhcmVuY3k/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB84d13655" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> keeps its dollars</a> at US banks; Tether keeps them i=
n a mystery (but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
3377885.258417/aHR0cHM6Ly90ZXRoZXIudG8vZW4vdHJhbnNwYXJlbmN5LyN1c2R0/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBf4d9ade8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> it says</a> mostly in US Treasury bill=
s).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33377885.258417/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMTUvY2lyY2xlLWlwby11c2Rj=
LWxvc3MtdG8tdGV0aGVyLW1heS1jb21wbGljYXRlLWxpc3RpbmctcGxhbnMtdXNkYy11c2R0P2N=
tcGlkPUJCRDExMTUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTExNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB189a04a8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">Olga Kharif, Sidhartha Shukla=C2=A0and Emi=
ly Nicolle reported</a> on Circle=E2=80=99s problems, of which the main one=
 might be that it is too mainstream and, thus, too easily substitutable wit=
h bank accounts<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Circle=E2=80=99s main product, the crypto stab=
lecoin USDC, is losing ground to chief competitor Tether=E2=80=99s namesake=
 token, eroding its importance in digital-asset markets. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Circle is based in Boston and Tether is regist=
ered in the British Virgin Islands. USDC is widely used in the US through e=
xchanges like Coinbase Global Inc., which owns a minority stake in Circle. =
As yields on US Treasuries soared toward 5%, many USDC holders swapped it f=
or dollars to take advantage of those high returns, said Kyle Samani, co-fo=
under of crypto investor Multicoin Capital.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CMost people who have access to USDC h=
ave access to US dollar bank accounts, so they naturally convert USDC to US=
D to accrue that yield,=E2=80=9D Samani said. =E2=80=9CHowever, most people=
 who are holding USDT do not have access to USD bank accounts, so they don=
=E2=80=99t care about the foregone yield.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you can easily move between banks and stabl=
ecoins, and banks pay 5% interest, you=E2=80=99ll move to a bank. If you ca=
n=E2=80=99t do that, then Tether gets to keep the interest.</p>
